        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>In one setup, this program captues the stucuture and kinematics in greater detail than has been possible to date.  Based on our single-dish observations, we expect the line strengths to be roughly 0.1-0.2 mJy per beam, so we aim to reach 20mJy per beam line sensitivity per 0.2 km/s channel. We require the high spectral resolution because on the smallest scales, the lines are expeted to be rather narrow (0.5 km/s). As we have MOPRA maps of all of the line transitions requested, we do not require use of the ACA to recover flux on large scales.  Two basebands are set to provide a total of 4GHz of continuum.  With the integration time to achieve the line sensitivity, the continuum basebands will reach an rms 0.025 mJy/beam, which corresponds to 5e20 cm^-2 with standard assumptions about dust emission over an area 16 square arcminutes.   We can achieve our goals with modest angular resolution (3'').

For continuum, it is possible to make use of scaled dust continuum maps at different wavelengths (such as ATLASGAL at 870 micron or Herschel SPIRE maps, Rathborne et al., priv. communication) to 3mm, so that we can compare the continuum flux on large scales.  ALMA's sensitivity is crucial for the success of this program. With its 34 12-m antennas, compared to the 6 at Plateau de Bure, the sensitivity and uv coverage does not compare to that of ALMA. For example, 8 hours of on-source integration are needed to reach the same continuum sensitivitiy (with the full BW) for one pointing at the PdBI. Naturally the full mosaic we propose (68 pointings) would take much longer. </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
