    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Massive stars drive the energy budget in galaxies, yet their formation is ill-constrained. Filametary dark clouds harbor the initial conditions for star formation, though studies of the structure and kinematics of high mass infrared-dark clouds (IRDC) have been limited to compact regions. We propose to survey a large-scale IRDC, G11, in the 3mm continuum and dense gas tracers, HCO+ and H13CO+, and outflow/shock tracer SiO, for all of which we have single dish data already in hand. With the line data we will study the small-scale motions of the core structures compared to the global cloud motions. Comparison of H13CO+ to HCO+ will enable us quantify collapse motions, and we will employ the SiO transiton to probe for outflows (broad lines) and possible remnant shocks (narrow lines) from the cloud formation event. Finally, the sensitive continuum will probe the fragmenation on small scales and highest densities, which are beam-diluted in our single-dish measurments. This high-density gas (n&gt;10^4 cm^-3) is critical to discerning between a trubulence-dominated medium or gravitationally collapsing medium on small scales, a hotly debated issue in turbulent star formation models. 
</prp:abstract>
